Unemployment is one of the most pressing global challenges of our time. And it is¬†not only a developing world issue. Even in high-income countries, political and economic shifts can trigger sudden spikes in joblessness. For example, economists have warned that the Trump administration‚Äôs efforts to downsize the U.S. federal government could temporarily push tens of thousands of workers‚Äîincluding contractors and bureaucrats‚Äîinto unemployment.

A 2024 Urban Institute study estimated that laying off 75% of the federal workforce could raise unemployment rates by¬†up to 2.5% in rural areas¬†and¬†1% in major cities¬†like Washington, D.C., highlighting how quickly employment trends can shift. But behind these fluctuations lies a deeper, more persistent divide:¬†the gender gap. Around the world, young women consistently face higher unemployment rates than their male counterparts, regardless of geography or income level. Despite rising education levels and career aspirations, women are more likely to encounter structural and cultural barriers to employment‚Äîbarriers that aren‚Äôt captured by headline economic figures alone.

import pandas as pd

world_data_sex_exploded = world_data_sex.explode(index_parts=True).reset_index()

world_data_sex_exploded['coords'] = world_data_sex_exploded['geometry'].apply(lambda x: x.exterior.coords.xy if x else ([], []))
world_data_sex_exploded['x'] = world_data_sex_exploded['coords'].apply(lambda x: x[0][0] if len(x[0]) > 0 else None)
world_data_sex_exploded['y'] = world_data_sex_exploded['coords'].apply(lambda x: x[1][0] if len(x[1]) > 0 else None)

def flatten_polygons(gdf):
    records = []
    for ix, row in gdf.iterrows():
        if row['geometry'] is not None and row['geometry'].geom_type == 'Polygon':
            xs, ys = row['geometry'].exterior.xy
            for x, y in zip(xs, ys):
                records.append({
                    'NAME': row['NAME'],
                    'obs_value': row['obs_value'],
                    'sex': row['sex'],
                    'x': x,
                    'y': y
                })
    return pd.DataFrame.from_records(records)

df_plot = flatten_polygons(world_data_sex_exploded)

df_plot_clean = df_plot.dropna(subset=['obs_value'])

p = (
    ggplot(df_plot_clean)
    + aes('x', 'y', group='NAME', fill='obs_value')
    + geom_polygon(color='white')
    + scale_fill_cmap("plasma")
    + labs(
        title="World Map: Unemployment Rate by Sex (latest available year)",
        fill="Unemployment Rate (%)"
    )
    + theme_void()
    + facet_wrap('~sex', labeller='label_both', ncol=1)

)
fig = p.draw()
fig.set_size_inches(18, 8)
fig.savefig("unemployment_map_vertical.png", dpi=150)
plt.close(fig)
display(Image(filename="unemployment_map_vertical.png"))

According to the¬†ILO (2023), youth (15‚Äì24) are¬†three times more likely¬†to be unemployed than adults, with the highest concentration of unemployed youth in¬†Africa and the Arab States.¬†These patterns are exacerbated by underdeveloped labor markets, political instability, and lack of access to education or vocational training.

But beyond geography lies another crucial dimension: gender. Who are the people being left behind?

10 relevant countries in terms of Unemployment

A closer look at the¬†10 most affected countries¬†uncovers a clear and persistent¬†gender gap.

In countries such as Occupied Palestinian Territory, Iraq, and South Africa, young women face unemployment rates 10 to 20 percentage points higher than young men. In Yemen, for instance, the female youth unemployment rate is 25%, compared to¬†12%¬†for males (mean from 2019 to 2023). These disparities are linked to restrictive gender norms, limited childcare and maternity protection and discrimination in hiring practices.

According to the¬†World Bank, ‚Äúin many countries, especially in the MENA region, women‚Äôs participation in the labor force remains among the lowest globally‚Äîeven when educational attainment is high.‚Äù

import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *

# Data preparation
df_bar = (
    df_unicef
    .groupby(['country', 'sex'], as_index=False)
    .agg({'obs_value': 'median'})
)

# 2. 10 countries with the highest median
top_countries = (
    df_bar.groupby('country')['obs_value']
    .median()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .head(10)
    .index.tolist()
)
df_bar = df_bar[df_bar['country'].isin(top_countries)]


p = (
    ggplot(df_bar, aes(x='country', y='obs_value', fill='sex'))
    + geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge')
    + labs(
        title='10 Relevant Countries',
        x='Country',
        y='Median Unemployment Rate (%)',
        fill='Sex'
    )
    + theme(axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1))
)

# colour choices
my_colors = {
    'Male': '#2471A3',
    'Female': '#E75480',
    'Total': '#7D3C98'
}

p = (
    ggplot(df_bar, aes(x='country', y='obs_value', fill='sex'))
    + geom_bar(stat='identity', position='dodge', width=0.5)
    + scale_fill_manual(values=my_colors)
    + labs(
        title='10 Relevant Countries',
        x='Country',
        y='Median Unemployment Rate (%)',
        fill='Sex'
    )
    + theme(
        axis_text_x=element_text(rotation=45, hjust=1, size=8),
        axis_text_y=element_text(size=8),
        axis_title_x=element_text(size=10),
        axis_title_y=element_text(size=10),
        legend_title=element_text(size=8),
        legend_text=element_text(size=7)
    )
)

from IPython.display import Image, display

p.save("bar_chart.png", width=8, height=4, dpi=150)

display(Image(filename="bar_chart.png"))

Unemployment Trends by Gender (2019‚Äì2023)

2021¬†marks a critical year: female unemployment¬†spiked dramatically, surpassing 10% globally‚Äîwhile male unemployment remained comparatively lower.¬†COVID-19 disproportionately impacted sectors employing women (hospitality, retail, education, healthcare).

This shart shows that while the general trend improved post-2021,¬†the gap between male and female youth unemployment persists.

import pandas as pd
from plotnine import *
from plotnine import annotate
from IPython.display import Image, display

df_line = (
    df_unicef
    .groupby(['time_period', 'sex'], as_index=False)
    .agg({'obs_value': 'mean'})
)

# colour choices
my_colors = {
    'Male': '#2471A3',
    'Female': '#E75480',
    'Total': '#7D3C98'
}

peak = df_line[(df_line['time_period'] == 2021) & (df_line['sex'] == 'Female')]

p = (
    ggplot(df_line, aes(x='time_period', y='obs_value', color='sex', group='sex'))
    + geom_line(size=2)
    + geom_point(size=4)
    + scale_color_manual(values=my_colors)
    + labs(
        title='Unemployment Trends by Gender (2019‚Äì2023)',
        x='Year', y='Percent (%)', color='Gender'
    )
    + theme(
        figure_size=(7, 5),
        axis_text=element_text(size=12),
        axis_title=element_text(size=14),
        legend_title=element_text(size=13),
        legend_text=element_text(size=11),
        plot_title=element_text(weight='bold', style='italic', size=18, ha='left')
    )
    + annotate(
        'text',
        x=2021,
        y=float(peak['obs_value']) + 0.5,
        label='Pandemic peak ‚Äì highest unemployment for females',
        ha='center',
        size=9,
        color='#333333'
    )
)

p.save("unemployment_trends.png", width=8, height=5, dpi=150)
display(Image(filename="unemployment_trends.png"))

Surprisingly, the correlation between GDP per capita and unemployment is weak. Countries with higher economic output still experience elevated youth unemployment, especially among women. For instance in South Africa, the GSP is high relative to region, yet unemployment exceeds 60%.

This reveals a crucial insight: wealth alone doesn‚Äôt guarantee inclusive labor markets. Structural inequalities -¬†particularly gender-based‚Äîrequire policy-specific interventions.

Code 
df_scatter = (
    df_unicef
    .groupby('country', as_index=False)['obs_value'].mean()
    .rename(columns={'obs_value': 'unemployment_rate'})
)

df_gdp = (
    df_meta
    .groupby('country', as_index=False)['GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)'].mean()
    .rename(columns={'GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$)': 'gdp_per_capita'})
)

# Merge of both
df_scatter = df_scatter.merge(df_gdp, on='country', how='inner')

from plotnine import *

p = (
    ggplot(df_scatter, aes(x='gdp_per_capita', y='unemployment_rate'))
    + geom_point(color='#2471A3', fill='white', size=1, alpha=0.6)
    + geom_smooth(method='lm', color='gray', linetype='solid', se=False)
    + labs(
        title='Unemployment vs GDP per Capita (2019‚Äì2023)',
        x='GDP per capita (constant 2015 US$) mean',
        y='Unemployment rate (%) mean'
    )
    + theme(
        figure_size=(6, 6),
        axis_text=element_text(size=8),
        axis_title=element_text(size=8),
        plot_title=element_text(weight='bold', style='italic', size=10)
    )
)

p.save("scatter_unemployment_gdp.png", width=5, height=4, dpi=150)
